# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: red-black-tree
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:red-black-tree/2-3-4-tree] In computer science, a **2–3–4 tree** (also called a **2–4 tree**) is a self-balancing data structure that can be used to implement dictionaries.
[src:red-black-tree/2-3-4-tree] 2–3–4 trees are B-trees of order 4; like B-trees in general, they can search, insert and delete in O(log *n*) time.
[src:red-black-tree/2-3-4-tree] One property of a 2–3–4 tree is that all external nodes are at the same depth.
[src:red-black-tree/2-3-4-tree] 2–3–4 trees are closely related to red–black trees by interpreting red links (that is, links to red children) as internal links of 3-nodes and 4-nodes, although this correspondence is not one-to-one.
[src:red-black-tree/2-3-4-tree] Left-leaning red–black trees restrict red–black trees by forbidding nodes with a single red right child, which yields a one-to-one correspondence between left-leaning red–black trees and 2–3–4 trees.
[src:red-black-tree/2-3-4-tree] Find the child whose interval contains the value to be inserted.
[src:red-black-tree/2-3-4-tree] If that child is a leaf, insert the value into the child node and finish.
[src:red-black-tree/2-3-4-tree] The simplest possibility to delete an element is to just leave the element there and mark it as "deleted", adapting the previous algorithms so that deleted elements are ignored.
[src:red-black-tree/2-3-4-tree] Deleted elements can then be re-used by overwriting them when performing an insertion later.
[src:red-black-tree/2-3-4-tree] However, the drawback of this method is that the size of the tree does not decrease.
[src:red-black-tree/2-3-4-tree] If a large proportion of the elements of the tree are deleted, then the tree will become much larger than the current size of the stored elements, and the performance of other operations will be adversely affected by the deleted elements.
[src:red-black-tree/2-3-4-tree] If the parent is a 2-node and the sibling is also a 2-node, combine all three elements to form a new 4-node and shorten the tree.
[src:red-black-tree/2-3-4-tree] (This rule can only trigger if the parent 2-node is the root, since all other 2-nodes along the way will have been modified to not be 2-nodes.
[src:red-black-tree/2-3-4-tree] Once the sought value is reached, it can now be placed at the removed entry's location without a problem because we have ensured that the leaf node has more than 1 key.
[src:red-black-tree/2-3-4-tree] Deletion in a 2–3–4 tree is O(log n), assuming transfer and fusion run in constant time (O(1)).
[src:red-black-tree/2-3-4-tree] Since 2–3–4 trees are similar in structure to red–black trees, parallel algorithms for red–black trees can be applied to 2–3–4 trees as well.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] In computer science, a **binary search tree** (**BST**), also called an **ordered** or **sorted binary tree**, is a rooted binary tree data structure with the key of each internal node being greater than all the keys in the respective node's left subtree and less than the ones in its right subtree.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] The time complexity of operations on the binary search tree is linear with respect to the height of the tree.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees allow binary search for fast lookup, addition, and removal of data items.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] Since the nodes in a BST are laid out so that each comparison skips about half of the remaining tree, the lookup performance is proportional to that of binary logarithm.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] BSTs were devised in the 1960s for the problem of efficient storage of labeled data and are attributed to Conway Berners-Lee and David Wheeler.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] The performance of a binary search tree is dependent on the order of insertion of the nodes into the tree since arbitrary insertions may lead to degeneracy; several variations of the binary search tree can be built with guaranteed worst-case performance.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] The basic operations include: search, traversal, insert and delete.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] BSTs with guaranteed worst-case complexities perform better than an unsorted array, which would require linear search time.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] The complexity analysis of BST shows that, on average, the insert, delete and search takes $\Theta (\log n)$ for n nodes.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] In the worst case, they degrade to that of a singly linked list: $O(n)$ .
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] To address the boundless increase of the tree height with arbitrary insertions and deletions, self-balancing variants of BSTs are introduced to bound the worst lookup complexity to that of the binary logarithm.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] AVL trees were the first self-balancing binary search trees, invented in 1962 by Georgy Adelson-Velsky and Evgenii Landis.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees can be used to implement abstract data types such as dynamic sets, lookup tables and priority queues, and used in sorting algorithms such as tree sort.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] The binary search tree algorithm was discovered independently by several researchers, including P.F.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] Windley, Andrew Donald Booth, Andrew Colin, Thomas N.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] The algorithm is attributed to Conway Berners-Lee and David Wheeler, who used it for storing labeled data in magnetic tapes in 1960.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] One of the earliest and popular binary search tree algorithm is that of Hibbard.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] The time complexity of a binary search tree increases boundlessly with the tree height if the nodes are inserted in an arbitrary order, therefore self-balancing binary search trees were introduced to bound the height of the tree to $O(\log n)$ .
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] Various **height-balanced** binary search trees were introduced to confine the tree height, such as AVL trees, Treaps, and red–black trees.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are also efficacious in sortings and search algorithms.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are also a fundamental data structure used in construction of abstract data structures such as sets, multisets, and associative arrays.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] Searching in a binary search tree for a specific key can be programmed recursively or iteratively.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] Searching begins by examining the root node.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] If the tree is nil, the key being searched for does not exist in the tree.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] Otherwise, if the key equals that of the root, the search is successful and the node is returned.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] If the key is less than that of the root, the search proceeds by examining the left subtree.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] Similarly, if the key is greater than that of the root, the search proceeds by examining the right subtree.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] This process is repeated until the key is found or the remaining subtree is ${\text{nil}}$ .
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] If the searched key is not found after a ${\text{nil}}$ subtree is reached, then the key is not present in the tree.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] The following pseudocode implements the BST search procedure through recursion.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] The recursive procedure continues until a ${\text{nil}}$ or the ${\text{key}}$ being searched for are encountered.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] The recursive version of the search can be "unrolled" into a while loop.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] On most machines, the iterative version is found to be more efficient.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] Since the search may proceed till some leaf node, the running time complexity of BST search is $O(h)$ where h is the height of the tree.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] However, the worst case for BST search is $O(n)$ where n is the total number of nodes in the BST, because an unbalanced BST may degenerate to a linked list.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] However, if the BST is height-balanced the height is $O(\log n)$ .
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] For certain operations, given a node ${\text{x}}$ , finding the successor or predecessor of ${\text{x}}$ is crucial.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] Assuming all the keys of a BST are distinct, the successor of a node ${\text{x}}$ in a BST is the node with the smallest key greater than ${\text{x}}$ 's key.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] On the other hand, the predecessor of a node ${\text{x}}$ in a BST is the node with the largest key smaller than ${\text{x}}$ 's key.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] The following pseudocode finds the successor and predecessor of a node ${\text{x}}$ in a BST.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] Operations such as finding a node in a BST whose key is the maximum or minimum are critical in certain operations, such as determining the successor and predecessor of nodes.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] Following is the pseudocode for the operations.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] Operations such as insertion and deletion cause the BST representation to change dynamically.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] The data structure must be modified in such a way that the properties of BST continue to hold.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] New nodes are inserted as leaf nodes in the BST.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] Following is an iterative implementation of the insertion operation.
