[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] After initialization on line 2, the **while** loop along lines 4-11 causes the pointers to be updated.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] If ${\text{y}}$ is ${\text{nil}}$ , the BST is empty, thus ${\text{z}}$ is inserted as the root node of the binary search tree ${\text{T}}$ , if it is not ${\text{nil}}$ , insertion proceeds by comparing the keys to that of ${\text{y}}$ on the lines 15-19 and the node is inserted accordingly.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] If ${\text{Z}}$ has only one child, the child node of ${\text{Z}}$ gets elevated by modifying the parent node of ${\text{Z}}$ to point to the child node, consequently taking ${\text{Z}}$ 's position in the tree, as shown in (b) and (c).
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] If ${\text{Y}}$ lies within ${\text{Z}}$ 's right subtree but is not ${\text{Z}}$ 's right child, as shown in (e), ${\text{Y}}$ first gets replaced by its own right child, and then it displaces ${\text{Z}}$ 's position in the tree.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] Alternatively, the in-order predecessor can also be used.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] The following pseudocode implements the deletion operation in a binary search tree.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] The ${\text{BST-Delete}}$ procedure deals with the 3 special cases mentioned above.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] Lines 2-3 deal with case 1; lines 4-5 deal with case 2 and lines 6-16 for case 3.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] The helper function ${\text{Shift-Nodes}}$ is used within the deletion algorithm for the purpose of replacing the node ${\text{u}}$ with ${\text{v}}$ in the binary search tree ${\text{BST}}$ .
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] This procedure handles the deletion (and substitution) of ${\text{u}}$ from ${\text{BST}}$ .
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] A BST can be traversed through three basic algorithms: inorder, preorder, and postorder tree walks.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] Following is a recursive implementation of the tree walks.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] Without rebalancing, insertions or deletions in a binary search tree may lead to degeneration, resulting in a height n of the tree (where n is number of items in a tree), so that the lookup performance is deteriorated to that of a linear search.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] Keeping the search tree balanced and height bounded by $O(\log n)$ is a key to the usefulness of the binary search tree.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] This can be achieved by "self-balancing" mechanisms during the updation operations to the tree designed to maintain the tree height to the binary logarithmic complexity.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] A tree is height-balanced if the heights of the left sub-tree and right sub-tree are guaranteed to be related by a constant factor.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] This property was introduced by the AVL tree and continued by the red–black tree.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] The heights of all the nodes on the path from the root to the modified leaf node have to be observed and possibly corrected on every insert and delete operation to the tree.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] In a weight-balanced tree, the criterion of a balanced tree is the number of leaves of the subtrees.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] The weights of the left and right subtrees differ at most by 1 .
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] However, the difference is bound by a ratio $\alpha$ of the weights, since a strong balance condition of 1 cannot be maintained with $O(\log n)$ rebalancing work during insert and delete operations.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] The $\alpha$ -weight-balanced trees gives an entire family of balance conditions, where each left and right subtrees have each at least a fraction of $\alpha$ of the total weight of the subtree.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] There are several self-balanced binary search trees, including T-tree, treap, red-black tree, B-tree, 2–3 tree, and Splay tree.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are used in sorting algorithms such as tree sort, where all the elements are inserted at once and the tree is traversed at an in-order fashion.
[src:red-black-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are used in implementing priority queues, using the node's key as priorities.
[src:red-black-tree/left-leaning-red-black-tree] A **left-leaning red–black** (**LLRB**) tree is a type of self-balancing binary search tree, introduced by Robert Sedgewick.
[src:red-black-tree/left-leaning-red-black-tree] It is a variant of the red–black tree and guarantees the same asymptotic complexity for operations, but is designed to be easier to implement.
[src:red-black-tree/left-leaning-red-black-tree] Every path from a given node to any of its descendant NIL nodes goes through the same number of black nodes.
[src:red-black-tree/left-leaning-red-black-tree] If a node has only one red child, it must be the left child.
[src:red-black-tree/left-leaning-red-black-tree] The left-leaning property reduces the number of cases that must be considered when implementing search tree operations.
[src:red-black-tree/left-leaning-red-black-tree] Unlike conventional red-black trees, the 3-nodes always lean left, making this relationship a 1 to 1 correspondence.
[src:red-black-tree/left-leaning-red-black-tree] This means that for every LLRB tree, there is a unique corresponding 2–3–4 tree, and vice versa.
[src:red-black-tree/left-leaning-red-black-tree] If we impose the additional requirement that a node may not have two red children, LLRB trees become isomorphic to 2–3 trees, since 4-nodes are now prohibited.
[src:red-black-tree/left-leaning-red-black-tree] Sedgewick remarks that the implementations of LLRB 2–3 trees and LLRB 2–3–4 trees differ only in the position of a single line of code.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] In computer science, a **red–black tree** is a self-balancing binary search tree data structure noted for fast storage and retrieval of ordered information.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The nodes in a red-black tree hold an extra "color" bit, often drawn as red and black, which help ensure that the tree is always approximately balanced.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] When the tree is modified, the new tree is rearranged and "repainted" to restore the coloring properties that constrain how unbalanced the tree can become in the worst case.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The properties are designed such that this rearranging and recoloring can be performed efficiently.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The (re-)balancing is not perfect, but guarantees searching in $O(\log n)$ time, where n is the number of entries in the tree.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The insert and delete operations, along with tree rearrangement and recoloring, also execute in $O(\log n)$ time.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Tracking the color of each node requires only one bit of information per node because there are only two colors (due to memory alignment present in some programming languages, the real memory consumption may differ).
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The tree does not contain any other data specific to it being a red–black tree, so its memory footprint is almost identical to that of a classic (uncolored) binary search tree.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] In some cases, the added bit of information can be stored at no added memory cost.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] In 1972, Rudolf Bayer invented a data structure that was a special order-4 case of a B-tree.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] These trees maintained all paths from root to leaf with the same number of nodes, creating perfectly balanced trees.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] However, they were not *binary* search trees.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Bayer called them a "symmetric binary B-tree" in his paper and later they became popular as 2–3–4 trees or even 2–3 trees.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] In a 1978 paper, "A Dichromatic Framework for Balanced Trees", Leonidas J.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Guibas and Robert Sedgewick derived the red–black tree from the symmetric binary B-tree.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The color "red" was chosen because it was the best-looking color produced by the color laser printer available to the authors while working at Xerox PARC.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Another response from Guibas states that it was because of the red and black pens available to them to draw the trees.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] In 1993, Arne Andersson introduced the idea of a right leaning tree to simplify insert and delete operations.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] In 1999, Chris Okasaki showed how to make the insert operation purely functional.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Its balance function needed to take care of only four unbalanced cases and one default balanced case.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The original algorithm used eight unbalanced cases, but Cormen et al.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] (2001) reduced that to six unbalanced cases.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Sedgewick showed that the insert operation can be implemented in just 46 lines of Java.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] In 2008, Sedgewick proposed the left-leaning red–black tree, leveraging Andersson’s idea that simplified the insert and delete operations.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Sedgewick originally allowed nodes whose two children are red, making his trees more like 2–3–4 trees, but later this restriction was added, making new trees more like 2–3 trees.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Sedgewick implemented the insert algorithm in just 33 lines, significantly shortening his original 46 lines of code.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The **black depth** of a node is defined as the number of black nodes from the root to that node (i.e. the number of black ancestors).
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The **black height** of a red–black tree is the number of black nodes in any path from the root to the leaves, which, by requirement 4, is constant (alternatively, it could be defined as the black depth of any leaf node).
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The black height of a node is the black height of the subtree rooted by it.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] In this article, the black height of a null node shall be set to 0, because its subtree is empty as suggested by the example figure, and its tree height is also 0.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Every path from a given node to any of its leaf nodes (that is, to any descendant null node) goes through the same number of black nodes.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] (Conclusion) If a node **N** has exactly one child, the child must be red.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] If the child were black, its leaves would sit at a different black depth than **N'**s null node (which is considered black by rule 2), violating requirement 4.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Cormen & al., claim "the root is black" as fifth requirement; but not Mehlhorn & Sanders or Sedgewick & Wayne.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Since the root can always be changed from red to black, this rule has little effect on analysis.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] This article also omits it, because it slightly disturbs the recursive algorithms and proofs.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] As an example, every perfect binary tree that consists only of black nodes is a red–black tree.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The read-only operations, such as search or tree traversal, do not affect any of the requirements.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] In contrast, the modifying operations insert and delete easily maintain requirements 1 and 2, but with respect to the other requirements some extra effort must be made, to avoid introducing a violation of requirement 3, called a **red-violation**, or of requirement 4, called a **black-violation**.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The requirements enforce a critical property of red–black trees: *the path from the root to the farthest leaf is no more than twice as long as the path from the root to the nearest leaf*.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The result is that the tree is height-balanced.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] For a mathematical proof see section Proof of bounds.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Red–black trees, like all binary search trees, allow quite efficient sequential access (e.g. in-order traversal, that is: in the order Left–Root–Right) of their elements.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] But they support also asymptotically optimal direct access via a traversal from root to leaf, resulting in $O(\log n)$ search time.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Red–black trees are similar in structure to 2–3–4 trees, which are B-trees of order 4.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] In 2–3–4 trees, each node can contain between 1 and 3 values and have between 2 and 4 children.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] These 2–3–4 nodes correspond to black node – red children groups in red-black trees, as shown in figure 1.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] It is not a 1-to-1 correspondence, because 3-nodes have two equivalent representations: the red child may lie either to the left or right.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The left-leaning red-black tree variant makes this relationship exactly 1-to-1, by only allowing the left child representation.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Since every 2–3–4 node has a corresponding black node, invariant 4 of red-black trees is equivalent to saying that the leaves of a 2–3–4 tree all lie at the same level.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Despite structural similarities, operations on red–black trees are more economical than B-trees.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] B-trees require management of vectors of variable length, whereas red-black trees are simply binary trees.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Red–black trees offer worst-case guarantees for insertion time, deletion time, and search time.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Not only does this make them valuable in time-sensitive applications such as real-time applications, but it makes them valuable building blocks in other data structures that provide worst-case guarantees.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] For example, many data structures used in computational geometry are based on red–black trees, and the Completely Fair Scheduler and epoll system call of the Linux kernel use red–black trees.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The AVL tree is another structure supporting $O(\log n)$ search, insertion, and removal.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] AVL trees can be colored red–black, and thus are a subset of red-black trees.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The worst-case height of AVL is 0.720 times the worst-case height of red-black trees, so AVL trees are more rigidly balanced.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The performance measurements of Ben Pfaff with realistic test cases in 79 runs find AVL to RB ratios between 0.677 and 1.077, median at 0.947, and geometric mean 0.910.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The performance of WAVL trees lies between AVL trees and red-black trees.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Red–black trees are also particularly valuable in functional programming, where they are one of the most common persistent data structures, used to construct associative arrays and sets that can retain previous versions after mutations.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The persistent version of red–black trees requires $O(\log n)$ space for each insertion or deletion, in addition to time.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] For every 2–3–4 tree, there are corresponding red–black trees with data elements in the same order.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The insertion and deletion operations on 2–3–4 trees are also equivalent to color-flipping and rotations in red–black trees.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] This makes 2–3–4 trees an important tool for understanding the logic behind red–black trees, and this is why many introductory algorithm texts introduce 2–3–4 trees just before red–black trees, even though 2–3–4 trees are not often used in practice.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] In 2008, Sedgewick introduced a simpler version of the red–black tree called the left-leaning red–black tree by eliminating a previously unspecified degree of freedom in the implementation.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The LLRB maintains an additional invariant that all red links must lean left except during inserts and deletes.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Red–black trees can be made isometric to either 2–3 trees, or 2–3–4 trees, for any sequence of operations.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The 2–3–4 tree isometry was described in 1978 by Sedgewick.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] With 2–3–4 trees, the isometry is resolved by a "color flip," corresponding to a split, in which the red color of two children nodes leaves the children and moves to the parent node.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The original description of the tango tree, a type of tree optimised for fast searches, specifically uses red–black trees as part of its data structure.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] As of Java 8, the HashMap has been modified such that instead of using a LinkedList to store different elements with colliding hashcodes, a red–black tree is used.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] This results in the improvement of time complexity of searching such an element from $O(m)$ to $O(\log m)$ where m is the number of elements with colliding hashes.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The read-only operations, such as search or tree traversal, on a red–black tree require no modification from those used for binary search trees, because every red–black tree is a special case of a simple binary search tree.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] However, the immediate result of an insertion or removal may violate the properties of a red–black tree, the restoration of which is called *rebalancing* so that red–black trees become self-balancing.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Rebalancing (i.e. color changes) has a worst-case time complexity of $O(\log n)$ and average of $O(1)$ , though these are very quick in practice.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Additionally, rebalancing takes no more than three tree rotations (two for insertion).
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] This is an example implementation of insert and remove in C.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Below are the data structures and the `rotate_subtree` helper function used in the insert and remove examples.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The proposal breaks down both insertion and removal (not mentioning some very simple cases) into six constellations of nodes, edges, and colors, which are called cases.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The proposal contains, for both insertion and removal, exactly one case that advances one black level closer to the root and loops, the other five cases rebalance the tree of their own.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The more complicated cases are pictured in a diagram.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] If a rotation is considered useful, this is pictured in the next action, which is labeled "rotation".
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] If some recoloring is considered useful, this is pictured in the next action, which is labeled "color".
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] If there is still some need to repair, the cases make use of code of other cases and this after a reassignment of the current node **N**, which then again carries a blue ring and relative to which other nodes may have to be reassigned also.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] For both, insert and delete, there is (exactly) one case which iterates one black level closer to the root; then the reassigned constellation satisfies the respective loop invariant.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Insertion begins by placing the new (non-NULL) node, say **N**, at the position in the binary search tree of a NULL node whose in-order predecessor’s key compares less than the new node’s key, which in turn compares less than the key of its in-order successor.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] But if its parent, say **P**, is also red then this action introduces a red-violation.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The current node’s parent **P** is black, so requirement 3 holds.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Requirement 4 holds also according to the loop invariant.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] If both the parent **P** and the uncle **U** are red, then both of them can be repainted black and the grandparent **G** becomes red for maintaining requirement 4.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Since any path through the parent or uncle must pass through the grandparent, the number of black nodes on these paths has not changed.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] However, the grandparent **G** may now violate requirement 3, if it has a red parent.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] After relabeling **G** to **N** the loop invariant is fulfilled so that the rebalancing can be iterated on one black level (= 2 tree levels) higher.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Insert case 2 has been executed for ${\tfrac {h-1}{2}}$ times and the total height of the tree has increased by 1, now being h .
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The current node **N** is the (red) root of the tree, and all RB-properties are satisfied.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Because **N** is also red, requirement 3 is violated.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] But after switching **P**’s color the tree is in RB-shape.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The black height of the tree increases by 1.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The parent **P** is red but the uncle **U** is black.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The ultimate goal is to rotate the parent node **P** to the grandparent position, but this will not work if **N** is an "inner" grandchild of **G** (i.e., if **N** is the left child of the right child of **G** or the right child of the left child of **G**).
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] A `dir`-rotation at **P** switches the roles of the current node **N** and its parent **P**.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The rotation adds paths through **N** (those in the subtree labeled **2**, see diagram) and removes paths through **P** (those in the subtree labeled **4**).
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] But both **P** and **N** are red, so requirement 4 is preserved.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The current node **N** is now certain to be an "outer" grandchild of **G** (left of left child or right of right child).
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] **G** is black and its former child **P** is red, since requirement 3 was violated.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] After switching the colors of **P** and **G** the resulting tree satisfies requirement 3.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Requirement 4 also remains satisfied, since all paths that went through the black **G** now go through the black **P**.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Because the algorithm transforms the input without using an auxiliary data structure and using only a small amount of extra storage space for auxiliary variables it is in-place.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The complex case is when **N** is not the root, colored black and has no proper child (⇔ only NULL children).
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] In the first iteration, **N** is replaced by NULL.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] One black node has been removed from every path, so the RB-properties are preserved.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The black height of the tree decreases by 1.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The sibling **S** is red, so **P** and the nephews **C** and **D** have to be black.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] A `dir`-rotation at **P** turns **S** into **N**’s grandparent.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Then after reversing the colors of **P** and **S**, the path through **N** is still short one black node.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] But **N** now has a red parent **P** and after the reassignment a black sibling **S**, so the transformations in cases 4, 5, or 6 are able to restore the RB-shape.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The sibling **S** and **S**’s children are black, but **P** is red.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Exchanging the colors of **S** and **P** does not affect the number of black nodes on paths going through **S**, but it does add one to the number of black nodes on paths going through **N**, making up for the deleted black node on those paths.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The sibling **S** is black, **S**’s close child **C** is red, and **S**’s distant child **D** is black.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] After a `(1-dir)`-rotation at **S** the nephew **C** becomes **S**’s parent and **N**’s new sibling.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The colors of **S** and **C** are exchanged.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] All paths still have the same number of black nodes, but now **N** has a black sibling whose distant child is red, so the constellation is fit for case D6.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Neither **N** nor its parent **P** are affected by this transformation, and **P** may be red or black ( in the diagram).
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The sibling **S** is black, **S**’s distant child **D** is red.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] After a `dir`-rotation at **P** the sibling **S** becomes the parent of **P** and **S**’s distant child **D**.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The colors of **P** and **S** are exchanged, and **D** is made black.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The whole subtree still has the same color at its root **S**, namely either red or black ( in the diagram), which refers to the same color both before and after the transformation.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Thus, the paths passing through **N** pass through one additional black node, so that requirement 4 is restored and the total tree is in RB-shape.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] nodes ( $\lfloor \,\rfloor$ is the floor function) and there is no red–black tree of this tree height with fewer nodes—therefore it is **minimal**.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] For a red–black tree of a certain height to have minimal number of nodes, it must have exactly one longest path with maximal number of red nodes, to achieve a maximal tree height with a minimal black height.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Besides this path all other nodes have to be black.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] If a node is taken off this tree it either loses height or some RB property.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The RB tree of height $h=1$ with red root is minimal.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] A minimal RB tree (RB*h* in figure 2) of height $h>1$ has a root whose two child subtrees are of different height.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The graph of the function $m_{h}$ is convex and piecewise linear with breakpoints at $(h=2k\;|\;m_{2k}=2\cdot 2^{k}\!-\!2)$ where $k\in \mathbb {N} .$ The function has been tabulated as $m_{h}=$ A027383(*h*–1) for $h\geq 1$ (sequence A027383 in the OEIS).
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] In addition to the single-element insert, delete and lookup operations, several set operations have been defined on red–black trees: union, intersection and set difference.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Then fast *bulk* operations on insertions or deletions can be implemented based on these set functions.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] These set operations rely on two helper operations, *Split* and *Join*.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] With the new operations, the implementation of red–black trees can be more efficient and highly-parallelizable.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] In order to achieve its time complexities this implementation requires that the root is allowed to be either red or black, and that every node stores its own **black height**.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The new node may invalidate the red–black invariant because at most three red nodes can appear in a row.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] This can be fixed with a double rotation.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] If double red issue propagates to the root, the root is then set to be black, restoring the properties.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The cost of this function is the difference of the black heights between the two input trees.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The union of two red–black trees *t*1 and *t*2 representing sets A and B, is a red–black tree t that represents *A* ∪ *B*.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Here, *split* is presumed to return two trees: one holding the keys less its input key, one holding the greater keys.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The algorithm for intersection or difference is similar, but requires the *Join2* helper routine that is the same as *Join* but without the middle key.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Based on the new functions for union, intersection or difference, either one key or multiple keys can be inserted to or deleted from the red–black tree.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] Since *Split* calls *Join* but does not deal with the balancing criteria of red–black trees directly, such an implementation is usually called the "join-based" implementation.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] The complexity of each of union, intersection and difference is $O\left(m\log \left({n \over m}+1\right)\right)$ for two red–black trees of sizes m and $n(\geq m)$ .
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] This complexity is optimal in terms of the number of comparisons.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] More importantly, since the recursive calls to union, intersection or difference are independent of each other, they can be executed in parallel with a parallel depth $O(\log m\log n)$ .
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p01] When $m=1$ , the join-based implementation has the same computational directed acyclic graph (DAG) as single-element insertion and deletion if the root of the larger tree is used to split the smaller tree.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] Parallel algorithms for constructing red–black trees from sorted lists of items can run in constant time or $O(\log \log n)$ time, depending on the computer model, if the number of processors available is asymptotically proportional to the number n of items where $n\to \infty$ .
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] Fast search, insertion, and deletion parallel algorithms are also known.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] The join-based algorithms for red–black trees are parallel for bulk operations, including union, intersection, construction, filter, map-reduce, and so on.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] Basic operations like insertion, removal or update can be parallelised by defining operations that process bulks of multiple elements.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] It is also possible to process bulks with several basic operations, for example bulks may contain elements to insert and also elements to remove from the tree.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] The algorithms for bulk operations aren't just applicable to the red–black tree, but can be adapted to other sorted sequence data structures also, like the 2–3 tree, 2–3–4 tree and (a,b)-tree.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] In the following different algorithms for bulk insert will be explained, but the same algorithms can also be applied to removal and update.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] Bulk insert is an operation that inserts each element of a sequence I into a tree T .
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] This approach can be applied to every sorted sequence data structure that supports efficient join- and split-operations.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] The general idea is to split I and T in multiple parts and perform the insertions on these parts in parallel.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] After that, the algorithm splits I into $k\in \mathbb {N} ^{+}$ parts $\langle I_{1},\cdots ,I_{k}\rangle$ of about equal sizes.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] Now the algorithm inserts each element of $I_{j}$ into $T_{j}$ sequentially.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] This step must be performed for every j, which can be done by up to k processors in parallel.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] Finally, the resulting trees will be joined to form the final result of the entire operation.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] Note that in Step 3 the constraints for splitting I assure that in Step 5 the trees can be joined again and the resulting sequence is sorted.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] The pseudo code shows a simple divide-and-conquer implementation of the join-based algorithm for bulk-insert.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] Both recursive calls can be executed in parallel.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] The join operation used here differs from the version explained in this article, instead join2 is used, which misses the second parameter k.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] Sorting I is not considered in this analysis.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] This can be improved by using parallel algorithms for splitting and joining.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] In this case the execution time is $\in O\left(\log |T|+{\frac {|I|}{k}}\log |T|\right)$ .
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] Another method of parallelizing bulk operations is to use a pipelining approach.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] This can be done by breaking the task of processing a basic operation up into a sequence of subtasks.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] For multiple basic operations the subtasks can be processed in parallel by assigning each subtask to a separate processor.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] For each element in I the algorithm locates the according insertion position in T.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] This can be done in parallel for each element $\in I$ since T won't be mutated in this process.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] Now I must be divided into subsequences S according to the insertion position of each element.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] For example $s_{n,{\mathit {left}}}$ is the subsequence of I that contains the elements whose insertion position would be to the left of node n.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] The middle element $m_{n,{\mathit {dir}}}$ of every subsequence $s_{n,{\mathit {dir}}}$ will be inserted into T as a new node $n'$ .
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] This can be done in parallel for each $m_{n,{\mathit {dir}}}$ since by definition the insertion position of each $m_{n,{\mathit {dir}}}$ is unique.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] If $s_{n,{\mathit {dir}}}$ contains elements to the left or to the right of $m_{n,{\mathit {dir}}}$ , those will be contained in a new set of subsequences S as $s_{n',{\mathit {left}}}$ or $s_{n',{\mathit {right}}}$ .
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] Now T possibly contains up to two consecutive red nodes at the end of the paths form the root to the leaves, which needs to be repaired.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] Note that, while repairing, the insertion position of elements $\in S$ have to be updated, if the corresponding nodes are affected by rotations.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] The steps 3 to 5 will be repeated on the new subsequences until S is empty.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] At this point every element $\in I$ has been inserted.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] Each application of these steps is called a *stage*.
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] Since the length of the subsequences in S is $\in O(|I|)$ and in every stage the subsequences are being cut in half, the number of stages is $\in O(\log |I|)$ .
[src:red-black-tree/red-black-tree-p02] Also, $|I|$ is assumed to be smaller than $|T|$ , otherwise it would be more efficient to construct the resulting tree from scratch.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] In computer science, a **self-balancing binary search tree** (BST) is any node-based binary search tree that automatically keeps its height (maximal number of levels below the root) small in the face of arbitrary item insertions and deletions.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] These operations when designed for a self-balancing binary search tree, contain precautionary measures against boundlessly increasing tree height, so that these abstract data structures receive the attribute "self-balancing".
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] For **height-balanced** binary trees, the height is defined to be logarithmic $O(\log n)$ in the number n of items.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] This is the case for many binary search trees, such as AVL trees and red–black trees.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Splay trees and treaps are self-balancing but not height-balanced, as their height is not guaranteed to be logarithmic in the number of items.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Self-balancing binary search trees provide efficient implementations for mutable ordered lists, and can be used for other abstract data structures such as associative arrays, priority queues and sets.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Most operations on a binary search tree (BST) take time directly proportional to the height of the tree, so it is desirable to keep the height small.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] In other words, the minimum height of a binary tree with *n* nodes is log2(*n*), rounded down; that is, $\lfloor \log _{2}n\rfloor$ .
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] However, the simplest algorithms for BST item insertion may yield a tree with height *n* in rather common situations.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] For example, when the items are inserted in sorted key order, the tree degenerates into a linked list with *n* nodes.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] The difference in performance between the two situations may be enormous: for example, when *n* = 1,000,000, the minimum height is $\lfloor \log _{2}(1,000,000)\rfloor =19$ .
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] If the data items are known ahead of time, the height can be kept small, in the average sense, by adding values in a random order, resulting in a random binary search tree.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] However, there are many situations (such as online algorithms) where this randomization is not viable.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Self-balancing binary trees solve this problem by performing transformations on the tree (such as tree rotations) at key insertion times, in order to keep the height proportional to log2(*n*).
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Although a certain overhead is involved, it is not bigger than the always necessary lookup cost and may be justified by ensuring fast execution of all operations.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] While it is possible to maintain a BST with minimum height with expected $O(\log n)$ time operations (lookup/insertion/removal), the additional space requirements required to maintain such a structure tend to outweigh the decrease in search time.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] For comparison, an AVL tree is guaranteed to be within a factor of 1.44 of the optimal height while requiring only two additional bits of storage in a naive implementation.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Therefore, most self-balancing BST algorithms keep the height within a constant factor of this lower bound.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] In the asymptotic ("Big-O") sense, a self-balancing BST structure containing *n* items allows the lookup, insertion, and removal of an item in $O(\log n)$ worst-case time, and ordered enumeration of all items in $O(n)$ time.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] For some implementations these are per-operation time bounds, while for others they are amortized bounds over a sequence of operations.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] These times are asymptotically optimal among all data structures that manipulate the key only through comparisons.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Self-balancing binary search trees can be used in a natural way to construct and maintain ordered lists, such as priority queues.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] They can also be used for associative arrays; key-value pairs are simply inserted with an ordering based on the key alone.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] In this capacity, self-balancing BSTs have a number of advantages and disadvantages over their main competitor, hash tables.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] One advantage of self-balancing BSTs is that they allow fast (indeed, asymptotically optimal) enumeration of the items *in key order*, which hash tables do not provide.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] One disadvantage is that their lookup algorithms get more complicated when there may be multiple items with the same key.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Self-balancing BSTs have better worst-case lookup performance than most hash tables ( $O(\log n)$ compared to $O(n)$ ), but have worse average-case performance ( $O(\log n)$ compared to $O(1)$ ).
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Self-balancing BSTs can be used to implement any algorithm that requires mutable ordered lists, to achieve optimal worst-case asymptotic performance.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] For example, if binary tree sort is implemented with a self-balancing BST, we have a very simple-to-describe yet asymptotically optimal $O(n\log n)$ sorting algorithm.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Similarly, many algorithms in computational geometry exploit variations on self-balancing BSTs to solve problems such as the line segment intersection problem and the point location problem efficiently.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] (For average-case performance, however, self-balancing BSTs may be less efficient than other solutions.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Self-balancing BSTs are flexible data structures, in that it is easy to extend them to efficiently record additional information or perform new operations.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] For example, one can record the number of nodes in each subtree having a certain property, allowing one to count the number of nodes in a certain key range with that property in $O(\log n)$ time.
[src:red-black-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] These extensions can be used, for example, to optimize database queries or other list-processing algorithms.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] In discrete mathematics, **tree rotation** is an operation on a binary tree that changes the structure without interfering with the order of the elements.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] A tree rotation moves one node up in the tree and one node down.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] It is used to change the shape of the tree, and in particular to decrease its height by moving smaller subtrees down and larger subtrees up, resulting in improved performance of many tree operations.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] There exists an inconsistency in different descriptions as to the definition of the **direction of rotations**.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] This article takes the approach of the directional movement of the rotating node.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] The right rotation operation as shown in the adjacent image is performed with *Q* as the root and hence is a right rotation on, or rooted at, *Q*.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] This operation results in a rotation of the tree in the clockwise direction.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] The inverse operation is the left rotation, which results in a movement in a counter-clockwise direction (the left rotation shown above is rooted at *P*).
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] The key to understanding how a rotation functions is to understand its constraints.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] In particular the order of the leaves of the tree (when read left to right for example) cannot change (another way to think of it is that the order that the leaves would be visited in an in-order traversal must be the same after the operation as before).
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] Another constraint is the main property of a binary search tree, namely that all nodes in the right subtree are greater than the parent and all nodes in the left subtree are less than the parent.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] Notice that the right child of a left child of the root of a sub-tree (for example node B in the diagram for the tree rooted at Q) can become the left child of the root, that itself becomes the right child of the "new" root in the rotated sub-tree, without violating either of those constraints.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] As seen in the diagram, the order of the leaves doesn't change.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] The opposite operation also preserves the order and is the second kind of rotation.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] Assuming this is a binary search tree, as stated above, the elements must be interpreted as variables that can be compared to each other.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] The alphabetic characters to the left are used as placeholders for these variables.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] In the animation to the right, capital alphabetic characters are used as variable placeholders while lowercase Greek letters are placeholders for an entire set of variables.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] The circles represent individual nodes and the triangles represent subtrees.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] Each subtree could be empty, consist of a single node, or consist of any number of nodes.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] When a subtree is rotated, the subtree side upon which it is rotated increases its height by one node while the other subtree decreases its height.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] This makes tree rotations useful for rebalancing a tree.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] Consider the terminology of **Root** for the parent node of the subtrees to rotate, **Pivot** for the node which will become the new parent node, **RS** for the side of rotation and **OS** for the opposite side of rotation.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] For the root Q in the diagram above, **RS** is C and **OS** is P.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] The programmer must also make sure that the root's parent points to the pivot after the rotation.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] Also, the programmer should note that this operation may result in a new root for the entire tree and take care to update pointers accordingly.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] The tree rotation renders the inorder traversal of the binary tree invariant.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] This implies the order of the elements is not affected when a rotation is performed in any part of the tree.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] Computing one from the other is very simple.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] There are also *double rotations*, which are combinations of left and right rotations.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] A *double left* rotation at X can be defined to be a right rotation at the right child of X followed by a left rotation at X; similarly, a *double right* rotation at X can be defined to be a left rotation at the left child of X followed by a right rotation at X.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] Tree rotations are used in a number of tree data structures such as AVL trees, red–black trees, WAVL trees, splay trees, and treaps.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] They require only constant time because they are *local* transformations: they only operate on 5 nodes, and need not examine the rest of the tree.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] A tree can be rebalanced using rotations.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] After a rotation, the side of the rotation increases its height by 1 whilst the side opposite the rotation decreases its height similarly.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] Therefore, one can strategically apply rotations to nodes whose left child and right child differ in height by more than 1.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] Self-balancing binary search trees apply this operation automatically.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] A type of tree which uses this rebalancing technique is the AVL tree.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] Can the rotation distance between two binary trees be computed in polynomial time?
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] The rotation distance between any two binary trees with the same number of nodes is the minimum number of rotations needed to transform one into the other.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] With this distance, the set of *n*-node binary trees becomes a metric space: the distance is symmetric, positive when given two different trees, and satisfies the triangle inequality.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] It is an open problem whether there exists a polynomial time algorithm for calculating rotation distance, though several variants of the rotation distance problem admit polynomial time algorithms.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] Daniel Sleator, Robert Tarjan and William Thurston showed that the rotation distance between any two *n*-node trees (for *n* ≥ 11) is at most 2*n* − 6, and that some pairs of trees are this far apart as soon as *n* is sufficiently large.
[src:red-black-tree/tree-rotation] Lionel Pournin showed that, in fact, such pairs exist whenever *n* ≥ 11.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] In computer science, a **WAVL tree** or **weak AVL tree** is a self-balancing binary search tree.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] WAVL trees are named after AVL trees, another type of balanced search tree, and are closely related both to AVL trees and red–black trees, which all fall into a common framework of **rank balanced trees**.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Like other balanced binary search trees, WAVL trees can handle insertion, deletion, and search operations in time *O*(log *n*) per operation.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] WAVL trees are designed to combine some of the best properties of both AVL trees and red–black trees.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] One advantage of AVL trees over red–black trees is being more balanced: they have height at most $\log _{\varphi }n\approx 1.44\log _{2}n$ (for a tree with n data items, where $\varphi$ is the golden ratio), while red–black trees have larger maximum height, $2\log _{2}n$ .
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] If a WAVL tree is created using only insertions, without deletions, then it has the same small height bound that an AVL tree has.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] On the other hand, red–black trees have the advantage over AVL trees in lesser restructuring of their trees.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] In AVL trees, each deletion may require a logarithmic number of tree rotation operations, while red–black trees have simpler deletion operations that use only a constant number of tree rotations.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] WAVL trees, like red–black trees, use only a constant number of tree rotations, and the constant is even better than for red–black trees.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] WAVL trees were introduced by Haeupler, Sen & Tarjan (2015).
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] The same authors also provided a common view of AVL trees, WAVL trees, and red–black trees as all being a type of rank-balanced tree.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Different binary search trees have different algorithms for insert/delete and balancing algorithms, making it difficult for a systematic study.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] The authors of Haeupler, Sen & Tarjan (2015) introduce the rank balanced trees framework for unifying the study of binary search tree by defining the rank binary tree, and each binary search tree follows by specific constraints applied to the rank function.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Note that the framework doesn't specify the algorithms in which these trees are implemented.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] A rank binary tree is a binary tree where each node x is associated with a rank r(x).
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] For a node x that is not the root, the *rank difference* is $r(p(x))-r(x)$ *,* and such a node is called an i-child if the rank difference is i.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] A node is of type $i,j$ if the rank difference of its left child and right child is i and j (disregarding ordering).
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] So far all these rules are symmetric for the left node and the right node.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Note that weak AVL tree generalizes the AVL tree by allowing for 2,2 type node.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] A simple proof shows that a weak AVL tree can be colored in a way that represents a red-black tree.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] So in a sense, weak AVL tree combines the properties of AVL tree and red-black tree.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] As with binary search trees more generally, a WAVL tree consists of a collection of nodes, of two types: internal nodes and external nodes.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] An internal node stores a data item, and is linked to its parent (except for a designated root node that has no parent) and to exactly two children in the tree, the left child and the right child.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] An external node carries no data, and has a link only to its parent in the tree.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] These nodes are arranged to form a binary tree, so that for any internal node x the parents of the left and right children of x are x itself.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] The external nodes form the leaves of the tree.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] The data items are arranged in the tree in such a way that an inorder traversal of the tree lists the data items in sorted order.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] What distinguishes WAVL trees from other types of binary search tree is its use of *ranks*.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] These are numbers, associated with each node, that provide an approximation to the distance from the node to its farthest leaf descendant.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Unlike in AVL trees, where ranks are defined to be the same as nodes' heights, ranks do not always equal to heights in WAVL trees.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] The *rank difference* of node x is defined as the difference between the rank of x's parent and the rank of x.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Searching for a key k in a WAVL tree is much the same as in any balanced binary search tree data structure.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] When a node with value equal to k is reached, or an external node is reached, the search stops.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] If the search stops at an internal node, the key k has been found.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] If instead, the search stops at an external node, then the position where k would be inserted (if it were inserted) has been found.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Inserting an internal node with key k into a WAVL tree requires a search for k in the tree, ending at an external node, then a replacement of that external node with the new internal node with two external children, and finally a rebalancing of the tree.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] The rebalancing step can be performed either top-down or bottom-up, but the bottom-up version of rebalancing is the one that most closely matches AVL trees.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Bottom-up rebalancing begins by considering the rank-difference between a node - initially the newly inserted node - and its parent.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] If there is no parent, balance is restored.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Before insertion began, the rank-difference between parent and node was 1 or 2, but that difference has been reduced by 1 because the subtree rooted at node has grown taller.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] If the new rank-difference between parent and node is 1, balance is restored.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Otherwise, if the sibling, the other child of parent, has a rank-difference of 1 with the parent, promote the parent - increase its rank by increasing the rank-differences between it and each of its children - and continue rebalancing with the old parent as the new node.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Finally, with rank-differences of 0 and 2 for node and sibling, one or two tree rotations, with associated adjustments to rank-differences, can restore balance.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] The in-between child of node is the one with key between the keys of node and parent.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] If the rank-difference for that child and node is 2, rotate to move node up in the tree and parent down, then demote parent - reduce its rank by adjusting the rank-differences around it - and balance is restored.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Otherwise, rotate to move the child up and the node down, then rotate again to move the child up and the parent down.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Promote the child, demote the node and parent, and balance is restored.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Thus, overall, the insertion procedure consists of a search, the creation of a constant number of new nodes, a logarithmic number of rank changes, and a constant number of tree rotations.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Deleting an internal node from a WAVL tree starts with ordinary binary search tree deletion.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] For an internal node with no external child, that means finding its successor in the tree, exchanging the node with its successor, and then removing the node from its new tree position, where its left child is necessarily an external node.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] To remove an internal node with an external child, replace the node with the other child.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Bottom-up rebalancing begins by considering the rank-difference between a node - initially, the node that replaced the deleted node - and its parent.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Before deletion began, the rank-difference between parent and node was 1 or 2, but that difference has been increased by 1 because the subtree rooted at node has shortened.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] If the parent now has two external children, the internal-node property is violated because the parent has rank 2.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] The parent must be demoted, and rebalancing continued with the parent as the node that is the root of the too-short subtree.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] If the node has no parent, balance is restored.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] If the rank-difference between node and parent has grown from 1 to 2, balance is restored.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Otherwise, if the sibling, the other child of parent, has a rank-difference of 2 with the parent, demote the parent - decrease its rank by decreasing the rank-differences between it and each of its children - and continue rebalancing with the old parent as the new node.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Otherwise, if the two children of the sibling have rank-differences of 2 with the sibling, demote the parent and the sibling and continue rebalancing with the old parent as the new node.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Finally, with rank-differences of 3 and 1 for node and sibling, and with sibling having a child with rank-difference 1, one or two tree rotations, with associated adjustments to rank-differences, can restore balance.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Identify the children of the sibling as the niece and the nephew, where the key of the niece lies between the keys of the parent and sibling, and the key of the nephew does not.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] If the rank-difference between sibling and nephew is 1, rotate to move sibling up and parent down, promote the sibling, and demote the parent once, at least, and twice, if necessary to avoid violating the internal-node property.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Otherwise, with the rank-difference between sibling and nephew as 1, rotate to move the niece up and the sibling down, rotate again to move the niece up and the parent down, promote the niece twice, demote the sibling once, and demote the parent twice.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] It is worthwhile to compare the result of a delete which would cause rotations at multiple levels in an AVL tree with the rotation and rank changes performed in a WAVL tree.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] In the second image the node with value 12 has been deleted followed by a right rotation and assigning of all external nodes rank zero.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Each search, insertion, or deletion in a WAVL tree involves following a single path in the tree and performing a constant number of steps for each node in the path.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] In a WAVL tree with n items that has only undergone insertions, the maximum path length is $\log _{\varphi }n\approx 1.44\log _{2}n$ .
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] If both insertions and deletions may have happened, the maximum path length is $2\log _{2}n$ .
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Therefore, in either case, the worst-case time for each search, insertion, or deletion in a WAVL tree with n data items is *O*(log *n*).
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Additionally, after finding a node for insertion and deletion, the amortized complexity of the tree restructuring operations is constant.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Adding or deleting the node itself is constant time, the amount of rotations is always at most constant and it can be shown that the total amount of rank changes in the nodes is linear in the number of both insertions and deletions.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] WAVL trees are closely related to both AVL trees and red–black trees.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Every AVL tree can have ranks assigned to its nodes in a way that makes it into a WAVL tree.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] And every WAVL tree can have its nodes colored red and black (and its ranks reassigned) in a way that makes it into a red–black tree.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] However, some WAVL trees do not come from AVL trees in this way and some red–black trees do not come from WAVL trees in this way.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] An AVL tree is a kind of balanced binary search tree in which the two children of each internal node must have heights that differ by at most one.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] The height of an external node is zero, and the height of any internal node is always one plus the maximum of the heights of its two children.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Thus, the height function of an AVL tree obeys the constraints of a WAVL tree, and we may convert any AVL tree into a WAVL tree by using the height of each node as its rank.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] The key difference between an AVL tree and a WAVL tree arises when a node has two children with the same rank or height.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] In an AVL tree, if a node x has two children of the same height h as each other, then the height of x must be exactly *h* + 1.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] In contrast, in a WAVL tree, if a node x has two children of the same rank r as each other, then the rank of x can be either *r* + 1 or *r* + 2.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] This is because rank is not strictly equal to height in WAVL tree.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] This greater flexibility in ranks also leads to a greater flexibility in structures: some WAVL trees cannot be made into AVL trees even by modifying their ranks, because they include nodes whose children's heights differ by more than one.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] However, we can say that all AVL trees are WAVL trees.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] AVL trees are WAVL trees without the type of node that has both children of rank difference 2.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] If a WAVL tree is created only using insertion operations, then its structure will be the same as the structure of an AVL tree created by the same insertion sequence, and its ranks will be the same as the ranks of the corresponding AVL tree.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] It is only through deletion operations that a WAVL tree can become different from an AVL tree.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] In particular this implies that a WAVL tree created only through insertions has height at most $\log _{\varphi }n\approx 1.44\log _{2}n$ .
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] The equivalence between the color-based and rank-based definitions can be seen, in one direction, by coloring a node black if its parent has greater rank and red if its parent has equal rank.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] In the other direction, colors can be converted to ranks by making the rank of a black node equal to the number of black nodes on any path to an external node, and by making the rank of a red node equal to its parent.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] The ranks of the nodes in a WAVL tree can be converted to a system of ranks of nodes, obeying the requirements for red–black trees, by dividing each rank by two and rounding up to the nearest integer.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Because of this conversion, for every WAVL tree there exists a valid red–black tree with the same structure.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Because red–black trees have maximum height $2\log _{2}n$ , the same is true for WAVL trees.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] However, there exist red–black trees that cannot be given a valid WAVL tree rank function.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] Despite the fact that, in terms of their tree structures, WAVL trees are special cases of red–black trees, their update operations are different.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] The tree rotations used in WAVL tree update operations may make changes that would not be permitted in a red–black tree, because they would in effect cause the recoloring of large subtrees of the red–black tree rather than making color changes only on a single path in the tree.
[src:red-black-tree/wavl-tree] This allows WAVL trees to perform fewer tree rotations per deletion, in the worst case, than red-black trees.
